Alan, thank you for making this very important point -- one which I
missed expressing, but which generally governs how I have worked with
inherited code.

Kent, Ron et al have always suggested this technique for dealing with
inherited code:

As you find bugs, write tests that expose the bugs, then fix the bugs.
As you need to refactor, write tests to help provide the safety net
during refactoring, then refactor.
As you need to understand, write tests to codify your understanding.

Over time, you end up with good tests for your code with a minimum of
investment. Like anything else in XP, you do as much as you need and no
more.

Of course, if someone else is pressuring you to write the tests because
he wants coverage, you can ask him this:

&quot;If I didn&#39;t spend 80 hours writing these tests, I could spend my time
writing each test as I need it and the rest of the time writing new
code. Given what I know about the code, I won&#39;t be any faster writing
tests whether I write them all at once or as I need them. With that in
mind, what would you like me to do? In the worst case, I need all the
tests up front and end up writing them now anyway. It looks like you
win.&quot;

How does that sound, everyone?

*********** REPLY SEPARATOR ***********

On 2002-03-18 at 10:41 Alan Bram wrote:
In this discussion, apparently we have been talking about
&quot;retrofitting&quot; unit tests for old code that never before had them. The
notion seems to be that each method in a class, or perhaps each public
method, should have a unit test.

I think this is wrong. I think, as J.B. said, that in such a case you
should concentrate on testing features, not simply methods.

I would say that for new code, where you&#39;re writing tests along with
your production code, it might make sense to try for a test per
(public) method. But that&#39;s because in this case you have the benefit
of thinking about the testing at the time you&#39;re writing the code. I
think you&#39;re more likely to design your code in such a way as to have
this make more sense. (The &quot;testing influences design&quot; notion.)

The problem I see with mindlessly (or even mindfully) writing a test
for each method, just to satisfy someone&#39;s idea that code coverage is
good, is that you&#39;re likely to (1) invest a lot of (or even a little)
time; and (2) generate a lot of test code (which will have to be
maintained, don&#39;t forget), for what will turn out to be little or no
benefit. I would bet that the marginal number of bugs found by
&quot;complete&quot; per-method tests over a more sensible per-feature approach,
both now and forever in the future, is very close to zero. At least
that&#39;s my impression based on my own experiences.

More is not always better.

I would be very curious to know if anyone can report on actual
(measured, quantitative) experiences that either support or refute
this.

